text:
GAME TO WATCH
SEATTLE SEAHAWKS (2-2) AT CINCINNATI BENGALS (4-0)
TV: Sunday, 1 p.m. ET, Fox (Thom Brennaman or Justin Kutcher, Charles Davis, Tony Siragusa)
Line: Bengals by 3
Story lines: A date with the NFL’s best secondary should tell us a lot about just how good Bengals QB Andy Dalton, WR A.J. Green and the rest of the Cincinnati offense are. The passing game has led the way to a 4-0 start, but Cincinnati might end up leaning on RBs Jeremy Hill and Giovani Bernard more this weekend. … The Bengals have averaged 30.7 ponts over their last seven regular-season games. … The absence of Seahawks RB Marshawn Lynch (hamstring) puts QB Russell Wilson into an even bigger role. He also seems to be at his best when Seattle is facing a stout run defense, which Cincinnati has. … Rookie return man Tyler Lockett headlines Seattle’s outstanding special teams.

USA TODAY Sports' Week 5 NFL picks
CHICAGO BEARS (1-3) AT KANSAS CITY CHIEFS (1-3)
TV: Sunday, 1 p.m. ET, Fox (Sam Rosen, John Lynch, Pam Oliver)
Line: Chiefs by 9½
Story lines: In their Week 4 win, The Bears’ evolving 3-4 defense, which had been allowing 135.7 yards rushing per game, held the Raiders to 70 (3.2 average) and 243 yards overall (4.3 a play). … The Chiefs didn’t score a touchdown last week, but their defense allowed one in all four of the Bengals’ red-zone trips. … Chiefs RB Jamaal Charles and Bears RB Matt Forte are two of the league’s best all-purpose backs. Forte has 500 combined yards, and Charles has 467.
USA TODAY FANTASY SPORTS
Week 5 fantasy football rankings
WASHINGTON REDSKINS (2-2) AT ATLANTA FALCONS (4-0)
TV: Sunday, 1 p.m. ET, Fox (Chris Myers, Ronde Barber, Jennifer Hale)
Line: Falcons by 7½
Story lines: With a victory, Atlanta would sweep the NFC East and own sole possession of first place in the NFC South with Carolina on bye. … Falcons RB Devonta Freeman has thrived under the outside zone-blocking scheme of offensive coordinator Kyle Shanahan (formerly of the Redskins), generating 342 yards from scrimmage and six rushing touchdowns on 54 touches over the past seven quarters. … The Redskins are 1-8 on the road under coach Jay Gruden. … Washington TE Jordan Reed shares the team lead with 24 catches but is out due to a concussion. WR DeSean Jackson (hamstring) also remains unavailable. ... Falcons WR Julio Jones slowed down last week and is questionable Sunday as he deals with toe and hamstring issues.
USA TODAY
Betcha didn't know: Time to start thinking playoffs?
JACKSONVILLE JAGUARS (1-3) AT TAMPA BAY BUCCANEERS (1-3)
TV: Sunday, 1 p.m. ET, CBS (Spero Dedes, Solomon Wilcots)
Line: Buccaneers by 3
Story lines: The Jags, who beat the Dolphins in Week 2, can sweep their Florida counterparts. … Since throwing two INTs in Week 1, Jacksonville QB Blake Bortles has thrown one in his last 122 attempts and has a career-long streak of 67 attempts without a pick. … Bucs rookie QB Jameis Winston has thrown a pick-six on his first pass of the game in two of his four starts. … Tampa Bay allowed six TDs in the opener but only seven total in the past three games. ... TE Julius Thomas (hand surgery) is questionable to make his Jacksonville debut.
NEW ORLEANS SAINTS (1-3) AT PHILADELPHIA EAGLES (1-3)
TV: Sunday, 1 p.m. ET, Fox (Joe Buck or Thom Brennaman, Troy Aikman, Pam Oliver)
Line: Eagles by 4½
Story lines: In their Week 4 loss, the Eagles ran 28 fewer plays on offense than the Redskins. Philadelphia’s defense was on the field for 41 minutes. QB Sam Bradford hasn’t been able to jump-start the offense, resulting in few points, short possessions and bad karma. … The Saints rank 27th against the run, yielding 123.2 yards a game. The Eagles have averaged a meager 70.0 yards rushing a game, and DeMarco Murray is the poster child for rushing inefficiency at 1.6 yards a carry. It won’t help if Eagles LT Jason Peters (quad) can’t go.
USA TODAY
Bell: NFL's return to Los Angeles seems both inevitable and hugely complicated
CLEVELAND BROWNS (1-3) AT BALTIMORE RAVENS (1-3)
TV: Sunday, 1 p.m. ET, CBS (Kevin Harlan, Rich Gannon, Dana Jacobson)
Line: Ravens by 6½
Story lines: Cleveland has allowed the most yards in the league. … With Steve Smith suffering from a back injury and doubtful to play, the Ravens need WRs Kamar Aiken and Marlon Brown to gain the trust of QB Joe Flacco, who is 13-1 against the Browns since 2008. In those games he has thrown 18 touchdown passes vs. seven interceptions. … With QB Josh McCown playing well, the Browns need to sustain drives against a Baltimore defense that has struggled without injured OLB Terrell Suggs.
ST. LOUIS RAMS (2-2) AT GREEN BAY PACKERS (4-0)
TV: Sunday, 1 p.m. ET, CBS (Ian Eagle, Dan Fouts, Evan Washburn)
Line: Packers by 9½
Story lines: RB Todd Gurley gained 146 yards in his second game, revitalizing the Rams offense. … All of Green Bay’s wins have come by double-digit margins. … The Packers’ offensive line had protection problems last weekend. Those must be fixed with one of the NFL’s best defensive fronts coming to town and getting RT Bryan Bulaga (knee) back would certainly help. … Packers QB Aaron Rodgers has a 127.9 passer rating against the Rams and is 3-0 against them.
USA TODAY FANTASY SPORTS
Your complete fantasy football guide to Week 5
BUFFALO BILLS (2-2) AT TENNESSEE TITANS (1-2)
TV: Sunday, 1 p.m. ET, CBS (Andrew Catalon, Steve Beuerlein, Steve Tasker)
Line: Bills by 2½
Story lines: The Bills have been penalized a league-leading 58 times. Two of their 17 infractions last week negated TDs. … Patriots QB Tom Brady and Giants QB Eli Manning routinely got rid of the ball in two seconds or less, greatly limiting sacks and quarterback hits from Buffalo’s vaunted front. Look for Titans QB Marcus Mariota to do the same. … Tennessee has allowed four completions longer than 40 yards. … Buffalo turns to RBs Anthony Dixon and newly signed Boom Herron with LeSean McCoy (hamstring) and Karlos Williams (concussion) injured.
ARIZONA CARDINALS (3-1) AT DETROIT LIONS (0-4)
TV: Sunday, 4:05 p.m. ET, Fox (Kenny Albert, Daryl Johnston, Holly Sonders)
Line: Cardinals by 2½
Story lines: Arizona had three turnovers last week after committing four in its first three games. … The Lions have averaged just 17 rushes per game and less than 3.0 yards a carry, both NFL worsts. However they face a Cardinals defense that was gashed by Rams rookie RB Todd Gurley in Week 4. … Detroit has lost six in a row to the Cardinals. … Arizona QB Carson Palmer is on pace to throw for 4,620 yards. His best is 4,274, in 2013, his first year with the Cardinals. ... Probable to return to action are Cardinals RB Andre Ellington (knee) and Lions LB DeAndre Levy (hip).
USA TODAY
Jason Garrett scolds Greg Hardy: Not how we operate as an organization
NEW ENGLAND PATRIOTS (3-0) AT DALLAS COWBOYS (2-2)
TV: Sunday, 4:25 p.m. ET, CBS (Jim Nantz, Phil Simms, Tracy Wolfson)
Line: Patriots by 8½
Story lines: The Cowboys get DE Greg Hardy and MLB Rolando McClain back from suspensions just in time to face the league’s No. 1 offense. LB Sean Lee (concussion) is also likely to return. … New England is averaging 39.7 points per game. The NFL record (1950 Los Angeles Rams) is 38.8. … Patriots WR Julian Edelman has evolved into Wes Welker 2.0. Edelman’s 30 catches are nearly double the total of TE Rob Gronkowski (16). … Patriots K Stephen Gostkowski holds the NFL record with 425 consecutive extra points. … Cowboys RBs Joseph Randle and Darren McFadden could have big days against a New England D that allows 4.9 yards per rush, tied for worst in the league.
DENVER BRONCOS (4-0) AT OAKLAND RAIDERS (2-2)
TV: Sunday, 4:25 p.m. ET, CBS (Greg Gumbel, Trent Green, Jamie Erdahl)
Line: Broncos by 4½
Story lines: The Broncos are 4-0 for the second time in three seasons, but three of the wins have come by a combined 16 points. … The Raiders’ resurgent pass rush could be a big problem for Denver QB Peyton Manning and his jigsaw O-line, which will again be without LT Ty Sambrailo. … The Broncos offense has struggled on third down, converting 36.4%. But the Raiders allowed 10 of 17 third-down conversions last week. … Raiders RB Latavius Murray was benched last week after fumbling and dropping two passes.
USA TODAY
QB Rank, Week 4: What's wrong with Colin Kaepernick?
SAN FRANCISCO 49ERS (1-3) AT NEW YORK GIANTS (2-2)
TV: Sunday, 8:30 p.m. ET, NBC (Cris Collinsworth, Al Michaels, Michele Tafoya)
Line: Giants by 7
Story lines: 49ers QB Colin Kaepernick is the face of an offense in utter disarray. His hold on the starting job may be slipping, but he is far from the Niners’ only problem. He’s getting little help from a leaky offensive line and a defense that has allowed 6.2 yards per snap. … The Giants have held a halftime lead in every game. The 49ers have been dreadful out of the gate, outscored 29-0 in the first quarter and 67-20 in the first half.
PITTSBURGH STEELERS (2-2) AT SAN DIEGO CHARGERS (2-2)
TV: Monday, 8:30 p.m. ET, ESPN (Mike Tirico, Jon Gruden, Lisa Salters)
Line: Chargers by 3
Story lines: Steelers WRs Antonio Brown and Martavis Bryant, who will debut after serving a four-game suspension, form one of the league’s most explosive receiving duos. … San Diego QB Philip Rivers gets his favorite target back, too, with TE Antonio Gates also back from a four-game ban. … The Chargers had four sacks last week after recording one in their first three games. … Chris Boswell, who replaces Josh Scobee, is Pittsburgh’s fourth kicker since the start of preseason.
PHOTOS: Week 5 games ranked by watchability
14. Jaguars at Buccaneers: Beyond bragging rights in Florida, there's not much at stake in this matchup of 1-3 teams. 13. Bears at Chiefs: The Bears finally got their first win of the season and now face the Chiefs' 28th-ranked pass defense. 12. Steelers at Chargers: Michael Vick still must prove he can keep the Steelers' offense rolling with Big Ben out. 11. 49ers at Giants: Colin Kaepernick needs to build confidence after his early season struggles. 10. Browns at Ravens: The Ravens are rested after playing on Thursday in Week 4, but the Browns are looking for the upset. 9. Cardinals at Lions: Both Arizona and Detroit are looking to shake off disappointing late losses in Week 4. 8. Saints at Eagles: Whether it's New Orleans or Philadelphia, one team will be hurting at 1-4 after this game. 7. Colts at Texans: The struggling Colts look to keep their AFC South streak alive in Houston. 6. Bills at Titans: The Bills defense looks to regroup against Marcus Mariota and the Titans offense. 5. Redskins at Falcons: Atlanta looks to ride its offense to a 5-0 start, but the Redskins are looking to jump to 3-2. 4. Broncos at Raiders: The Broncos won't be able to coast in this AFC West trip to Oakland. 3. Patriots at Cowboys: Greg Hardy added some star power to this matchup with his midweek comments on Tom Brady. 2. Rams at Packers: The Rams tend to play up for their competition, but can they keep pace with Aaron Rodgers and Co.? 1. Seahawks at Bengals: The Bengals offense is rolling, while Russell Wilson and the Seahawks are still looking for answers.
